{
  "id": "c-mo2c33rv-0d22e9372938",
  "goal": "What writ link types are already in use across the guild?",
  "status": "concluded",
  "createdAt": "2026-04-17T03:13:38.779Z",
  "parentId": "c-mo1mqdk0-d0a1cc3c08c5",
  "conclusion": "100 links in use across 12 distinct types (queried books_clerk_links on 2026-04-17):\n\n  refines       30\n  retries       23\n  fulfilled_by  21\n  depends on     9   ← space-separated\n  builds-on      5\n  instance_of    3\n  enhances       2\n  fixes          2\n  relates-to     2\n  depends-on     1   ← hyphenated (same semantic as \"depends on\")\n  related        1   ← same semantic as \"relates-to\"\n  supersedes     1\n\nFootgun evidence realized in the data:\n\n- Typo drift: \"depends on\" (9) vs \"depends-on\" (1) — same semantic, two spellings. String-matching either one misses ~90% of the dependency data. \"blocked-by\" (the name the MVP click assumes) doesn't appear at all.\n- Overlapping synonyms: relates-to/related; refines/builds-on/enhances — taxonomy drift, no canonical form.\n- Three separator conventions coexist: space (\"depends on\"), hyphen (\"depends-on\", \"relates-to\", \"builds-on\"), underscore (\"fulfilled_by\", \"instance_of\"). No convention enforcement.\n\nConclusion: the open-string type field has already produced inconsistent usage at the 100-link scale. Any mechanism that relies on Spider/consumer code string-matching specific type names will have silent misses on existing data unless a canonicalization pass or a reserved-name enforcement mechanism is adopted.",
