content.content:
{
  "id": "c-mo2dbey3-b8e497ebd8c8",
  "goal": "How is polarity/direction represented for names that reverse a meaning's canonical direction (e.g., 'blocks' vs 'blocked by')?",
  "status": "concluded",
  "createdAt": "2026-04-17T03:48:06.124Z",
  "parentId": "c-mo2c3bs8-a876bbc50364",
  "conclusion": "Polarity lives in the semanticMeaning schema alone. Each registered meaning carries a canonical direction (e.g. precedence-gate: source writ is blocked until target writ completes). Names themselves carry no polarity metadata — consistent with the open pairing policy (names are free labels, not registry entries).\n\nAuthors control edge direction by choosing which writ is source and which is target, and pick whatever name reads naturally for that direction. If the author wants \"A blocks B\" semantics (B is gated by A), they create the edge as B→A with any fitting name (\"blocks\", \"blocked by\", \"requires\", etc.). The system interprets based on the meaning's canonical direction; the name is purely human-facing.\n\nThis dissolves the name-direction mismatch problem (e.g. \"blocks\" vs \"blocked by\" reading as the same concept but opposite polarity) — the system simply doesn't look at names for direction; direction is a property of the meaning.",
  "resolvedAt": "2026-04-17T04:05:23.158Z",
  "links": {
    "outbound": [],
    "inbound": []
  },
